1
00:00:01,600 --> 00:00:09,365
I want to continue with the discourse on the destruction of craving, the Mahatana Sankhaya Sutta.

2
00:00:11,016 --> 00:00:19,911
Here we find the Buddha countering a disciple's view that we have just the one consciousness that speaks, feels and experiences.

3
00:00:21,274 --> 00:00:28,365
The Buddha debunks this and reiterates his position that there are six distinct forms of consciousness.

4
00:00:29,246 --> 00:00:32,652
When we're seeing something, we have visual consciousness.

5
00:00:32,633 --> 00:00:35,840
When we're feeling hot, we have body consciousness and so on.

6
00:00:36,841 --> 00:00:43,857
Only one of these can operate at any moment, and it needs certain conditions to be present for that consciousness to arise.

7
00:00:45,222 --> 00:00:52,911
As an aside, I'd like to clarify that the Buddha is talking of worldly consciousness here, termed vijnana in Pali.

8
00:00:53,774 --> 00:00:59,240
There is ongoing debate about how we can describe awareness which transcends the world, nibbana.

9
00:01:00,161 --> 00:01:01,223
Let's not get into that.

10
00:01:02,045 --> 00:01:11,617
But remember that when we're speaking of consciousness starting and ending with each sensory experience, we're only referring to ordinary human consciousness here.

11
00:01:13,893 --> 00:01:20,343
The remainder of the Sutta gives us a methodology that lets us experience the world in the same way as the Buddha.

12
00:01:21,787 --> 00:01:26,454
In the first place, we are to learn to see experience as a series of happenings.

13
00:01:27,396 --> 00:01:32,424
The phrase he uses to describe this perspective is, this has come to be.

14
00:01:33,468 --> 00:01:37,218
When we get angry we can reflect anger has come to be.

15
00:01:37,257 --> 00:01:43,112
When we cool down and become peaceful we can reflect peace has come to be.

16
00:01:43,153 --> 00:01:50,311
Our whole life can be seen as a series of experiences arising one after the other.

17
00:01:53,346 --> 00:02:05,813
Normally, we use a broad-based understanding to negotiate the world, where we're aware of multiple things, the walls, the furniture, the conversation on the radio, the twinge of pain in the back.

18
00:02:06,876 --> 00:02:11,085
This broad understanding requires conceptualisation.

19
00:02:11,064 --> 00:02:15,633
It's a cognitive miracle, but it doesn't reflect ultimate reality.

20
00:02:16,854 --> 00:02:31,419
To experience ultimate reality, things as they really are, we have to be prepared to delve beneath thought to let awareness rest on the raw data that is coming through our sense doors moment after moment.

21
00:02:35,483 --> 00:02:40,831
With this intuitive awareness, we realize that we can only focus on one thing at a time.

22
00:02:41,854 --> 00:02:45,560
Whatever has just come to be, that is all we know.

23
00:02:45,599 --> 00:02:47,704
It's the limit of cognition.

24
00:02:48,544 --> 00:02:50,328
When we're seeing, we're not hearing.

25
00:02:51,270 --> 00:02:54,555
When we're hearing, we're not aware of the twinge in our back.

26
00:02:55,531 --> 00:03:07,009
At times we become painfully aware of how unsatisfactory this is to our normal sense of self, how little the self likes this stop-start world where certainties crumble.

27
00:03:08,532 --> 00:03:21,555
The pain of this insight, however, gives us an extra incentive to see how we can reduce the stress, learn to live peacefully with uncertainty, with the inability to control experience.

28
00:03:24,472 --> 00:03:34,311
Having persuaded ourselves that experience can be described as this has come to be the Buddha next wants us to learn about the causes and conditions for experience.

29
00:03:35,212 --> 00:03:39,180
Essentially, he says, all conditions have craving at their source.

30
00:03:40,342 --> 00:03:41,384
It's a sobering thought.

31
00:03:42,387 --> 00:03:45,652
Craving is obviously a very powerful force in the universe.

32
00:03:46,712 --> 00:03:49,796
Luckily, wisdom is an even stronger force.

33
00:03:50,717 --> 00:03:58,587
So we don't have to tackle craving head on, suppress every urge to want things to be different, accept every misery without reaction.

34
00:03:59,188 --> 00:04:00,310
This would be impossible.

35
00:04:01,592 --> 00:04:13,766
The Buddha discovered that craving can be undermined and eventually destroyed altogether by learning from direct experience about all the causes and conditions that underlie it.

36
00:04:13,747 --> 00:04:18,314
Just knowing these is to reduce and eventually eliminate craving.

37
00:04:20,158 --> 00:04:21,220
The power of knowing.

38
00:04:22,100 --> 00:04:22,961
It is amazing.

39
00:04:24,245 --> 00:04:27,790
By knowing is meant direct present moment conscious experience.

40
00:04:29,093 --> 00:04:38,809
It's because we don't fully know this, we skim over it, ignore so much of it, that we unwittingly allow craving to hold such sway in our lives.

41
00:04:40,173 --> 00:04:46,901
To the degree that we're skimming over, ignoring, we are, using Buddha's terminology, ignorant.

42
00:04:48,942 --> 00:04:57,673
In this sutta, the Buddha traces the causes and conditions for craving down to ignorance, this imperfect, imprecise knowing.

43
00:04:59,214 --> 00:05:04,341
He then recaps on the sequence, working back up from ignorance to dukkha.

44
00:05:08,235 --> 00:05:17,728
It's generally accepted that all the links up as far as sense contact occur simultaneously with the remaining ones following sequentially.

45
00:05:19,149 --> 00:05:29,601
At the deepest level of concentration we might see the final links from feeling onward to dukkha following one another in a flash.

46
00:05:30,603 --> 00:05:37,331
So the full sequence may be happening thousands, perhaps millions of times during every second of our lives.

47
00:05:38,576 --> 00:05:47,492
Although our concentration isn't sharp enough to follow each individual link, we can get to know each step when we focus attention.

48
00:05:48,654 --> 00:05:59,134
For example, we could focus on craving, looking within experience for pushing or pulling sensations, for rushes of energy,

49
00:05:59,113 --> 00:06:02,677
for the mind's tendency to narrow down on what it craves.

50
00:06:03,899 --> 00:06:11,848
In time, we'll be able to recognize craving and make a rational decision about whether or not to follow its suggestion.

51
00:06:15,632 --> 00:06:21,439
Similarly, we can learn by bringing attention to any stage independent arising.

52
00:06:22,880 --> 00:06:26,504
Eventually, intuition will use this knowledge wisely.

53
00:06:28,257 --> 00:06:36,488
We'll use that as a theme for the rest of the talk, asking how understanding this stage might release us from suffering.

54
00:06:41,636 --> 00:06:56,036
We get to know the first stage, ignorance, avijja, when we watch our relationship with not knowing, the little question mark in our minds that sometimes becomes evident as we sit in meditation.

55
00:06:57,889 --> 00:07:00,593
Not knowing isn't itself due to ignorance.

56
00:07:01,836 --> 00:07:03,577
There are real limits to cognition.

57
00:07:04,720 --> 00:07:07,463
For example, we don't know what's going to happen tomorrow.

58
00:07:08,665 --> 00:07:10,668
When we're hearing, we're not seeing.

59
00:07:12,110 --> 00:07:14,795
Appreciating how little we know is wise.

60
00:07:16,177 --> 00:07:20,944
It's the degree to which we're disturbed that gives a measure of our ignorance.

61
00:07:25,192 --> 00:07:34,242
There's a lot of purification to be had by learning to steady the mind around the sense of not knowing, if ever that comes up for you.

62
00:07:34,281 --> 00:07:49,377
Bearing with any agitation, restlessness, doubt or whatever hindrance comes up, the mind gradually makes peace with not knowing the future, not even knowing a sensation that passed a moment ago.

63
00:07:53,053 --> 00:07:58,420
The pause between breaths is sometimes when the sense of not knowing looms large.

64
00:08:01,084 --> 00:08:11,235
As we learn to steady the mind around that, we also get a sense of there being a potential for something to be brought into consciousness, to become known.

65
00:08:11,295 --> 00:08:18,184
This allows us to learn about the next stage independent arising, Sankara.

66
00:08:19,783 --> 00:08:25,651
Focusing on this sense of potential, we sense the somewhat ghostly nature of Sankara.

67
00:08:27,252 --> 00:08:32,559
All our usual avenues for experience are there, but being held back.

68
00:08:36,504 --> 00:08:42,633
Sankara, remember, are the habits we've developed through our previous thoughts, speech and actions.

69
00:08:44,053 --> 00:08:48,659
They're the fruits of karma and exist as a potential for their own repetition.

70
00:08:50,277 --> 00:08:56,303
What we want to avoid doing is repeating unskillful habits based on greed, hatred or delusion.

71
00:08:58,306 --> 00:09:05,394
When ignorance is strong, it's easy to identify with that question mark and fall prey to the hindrance of doubt.

72
00:09:07,317 --> 00:09:16,587
Then there might be temptation to rush into something, to choose any old course of action, rather than live with doubt and uncertainty.

73
00:09:19,471 --> 00:09:27,086
Better to recognize doubt and learn to dwell more peacefully within that state of wonder and potential.

74
00:09:30,793 --> 00:09:40,212
Bringing wisdom to these crucial early steps in the chain allows intuitive awareness to bring forth the most appropriate Sankara.

75
00:09:41,965 --> 00:09:43,927
Sankaras take three forms.

76
00:09:44,827 --> 00:09:48,873
Mental formations, which reflect our habitual feelings and perceptions.

77
00:09:50,315 --> 00:09:55,260
Verbal formations, which reflect our habits of thought and evaluation.

78
00:09:56,923 --> 00:10:04,951
And bodily formations, such as the in and out breath, which is the bodily habit we're most aware of in formal meditation.

79
00:10:08,914 --> 00:10:12,801
Let's look at some examples of working skillfully with Sankara.

80
00:10:14,943 --> 00:10:24,940
As we sit in meditation and things quieten down, during a pause between breaths, the little question mark of wonder might grow strong.

81
00:10:27,062 --> 00:10:32,711
We sense the tempting potential to think about what might be happening, what we should do.

82
00:10:34,260 --> 00:10:42,575
We also sense thinking being held back, recognized as a form of greed, the greed for understanding and control.

83
00:10:42,634 --> 00:10:51,168
In that case, body Sankara might be the wise route for conscious experience.

84
00:10:51,188 --> 00:10:58,902
Consciousness of breath gets stronger and stronger, steadying the mind against the temptation to indulge thought.

85
00:10:59,118 --> 00:11:08,711
Here, intuition has chosen bodhisankara as the basis for conscious experience and our habitual urge to think is undermined.

86
00:11:12,196 --> 00:11:17,582
At other times, feeling and perception may be the most skilful habit to come into consciousness.

87
00:11:19,206 --> 00:11:26,154
If the uncertainty has brought up strong aversion, the habit of metta would help us bear with this.

88
00:11:27,485 --> 00:11:38,899
If we've been practicing Metta in the past, then a perception of friendliness with associated pleasant feelings might emerge from nowhere, so to speak, to balance the aversion.

89
00:11:40,760 --> 00:11:47,149
In this case, intuition chose the mental habit of Metta as the basis for conscious experience.

90
00:11:49,152 --> 00:11:56,039
We begin to trust that this strange, uncertain world is, at base, a friendly place.

91
00:11:59,833 --> 00:12:13,940
Verbal Sankara can also be the skilful choice, especially when that sense of not knowing brings an almost chaotic bewilderment, as if we're an alien not understanding anything about the world.

92
00:12:16,544 --> 00:12:23,918
At such times, I found the phrase, this has come to be, surprisingly calming and consoling.

93
00:12:25,754 --> 00:12:34,070
It puts some sort of sensible framework around experience, reminding me that I'm just a human being in a state of bewilderment.

94
00:12:36,073 --> 00:12:46,934
In these cases, intuitive awareness has chosen to work through verbal Sankara, allowing the thought, this has come to be, become conscious.

95
00:12:51,943 --> 00:13:00,739
Sankara, the habits that emerge because of ignorance, form the basis for the next link, vijnana, consciousness.

96
00:13:03,486 --> 00:13:09,676
To get to know this link, we could try to verify the Buddha's insight that there are six distinct types.

97
00:13:10,677 --> 00:13:15,784
For example, while listening to a piece of music, look at some visible object.

98
00:13:16,725 --> 00:13:20,171
Can you really hear and see at the same time?

99
00:13:21,472 --> 00:13:23,556
Or does one or other tend to predominate?

100
00:13:25,398 --> 00:13:30,085
In standing meditation, can you really feel both feet on the floor?

101
00:13:31,515 --> 00:13:34,399
Or does attention keep switching from one to the other?

102
00:13:38,706 --> 00:13:48,681
Consciousness is coupled together with the following link, Nama-Rupa, mind and matter, like two sheaves of wheat balancing one another.

103
00:13:50,724 --> 00:13:59,716
Rupa refers to the matter which, in subjective experience, corresponds to four elements, earth, air, water and fire.

104
00:14:01,957 --> 00:14:08,744
Rupa, though physical in origin, is brought into mind through sense contact.

105
00:14:10,605 --> 00:14:15,830
Remember the first six links up as far as sense contact occur simultaneously.

106
00:14:18,692 --> 00:14:23,317
Here we can see how intertwined are the links of dependent origination.

107
00:14:25,639 --> 00:14:31,965
Sense contact forms a component of the mind that allows for sense contact to be made

108
00:14:33,413 --> 00:14:35,557
It's not a neat linear process.

109
00:14:37,081 --> 00:14:41,371
It's more like an ecosystem with everything intertwined.

110
00:14:41,412 --> 00:14:50,815
Other constituents of mind include intention and attention.

111
00:14:52,533 --> 00:15:04,309
Intention, otherwise called will or volition, is the basis for karma, which we create at a much later stage in the cycle, the stage termed becoming.

112
00:15:07,995 --> 00:15:16,667
Intention arises at this early stage, nama-rupa, and then does its business, so to speak, at the much later stage of becoming.

113
00:15:20,106 --> 00:15:32,402
If a Sankara of greed underlies consciousness, it is this mental factor of intention which allows greed to be acted out in the world and also be carried forward into the future.

114
00:15:33,964 --> 00:15:38,188
It's not the thought, act or speech themselves which create karma.

115
00:15:39,370 --> 00:15:42,333
The key is the will with which this has been done.

116
00:15:45,942 --> 00:15:56,994
Exactly the same thought, speech or action could have been done out of goodwill, resulting in a sankhara of metta, stirring a new round of conscious experience in the world.

117
00:15:58,674 --> 00:16:09,586
To incline our lives in the direction of freedom, we need to get to know what our motivations are, pull ourselves away from situations if we find they are unskillful.

118
00:16:13,802 --> 00:16:18,130
Attention is another mental factor which we can learn to use skillfully.

119
00:16:19,393 --> 00:16:22,678
We are constantly being bombarded with sensory information.

120
00:16:24,041 --> 00:16:29,029
Attention is the mental factor that selects out some portion of this to focus on.

121
00:16:31,533 --> 00:16:37,784
When we're not being mindful, we're letting Sankara, our old ghosts, tell us what to notice.

122
00:16:39,200 --> 00:16:41,364
Greed gets us to look for pleasure.

123
00:16:42,326 --> 00:16:47,054
Aversion lures attention towards whatever frightens or irritates us.

124
00:16:48,157 --> 00:16:59,097
Delusion persuades us to ignore incoming sense data so that we can prioritise daydreams, worries and plans, all of which bolster the concept of me.

125
00:17:00,495 --> 00:17:06,423
By contrast, mindfulness teaches us to bring attention to what will support our spiritual life.

126
00:17:07,423 --> 00:17:12,148
For example, the neutral sensations from the breath, which promote tranquility.

127
00:17:17,375 --> 00:17:23,781
Mind and matter form the necessary basis for the next link, the six sense doors.

128
00:17:25,203 --> 00:17:29,929
We have the five physical senses plus the mind itself as another sense door.

129
00:17:31,208 --> 00:17:36,193
The eyes are sensitive to light and can act as a doorway for visual consciousness.

130
00:17:37,215 --> 00:17:41,741
Similarly for the ears and sound, nose and odours and so on.

131
00:17:46,227 --> 00:17:52,595
Let's look in a bit more detail at the sixth sense, the mind as the doorway for mental consciousness.

132
00:17:54,837 --> 00:17:57,721
When we're looking at mind as part of Nama Rupa,

133
00:17:58,731 --> 00:18:12,893
we were looking at what you might call central headquarters, the aspects of mind that display and process information via feeling and perception, and control experience through attention and intention.

134
00:18:14,576 --> 00:18:19,645
The mind door, on the other hand, represents the receptive aspect of mind.

135
00:18:20,989 --> 00:18:32,088
It's the mind as a sensor, sensitive to its own activity, much as the eyes are sensitive to light and the ears to vibration.

136
00:18:33,791 --> 00:18:36,416
A detector which detects itself.

137
00:18:38,843 --> 00:18:44,848
When we listen to our own thoughts, we are using the mind as a sense door.

138
00:18:48,913 --> 00:18:50,556
It's mind-boggling to think about.

139
00:18:50,596 --> 00:18:54,319
No wonder we're in such a state of confusion.

140
00:18:55,401 --> 00:19:06,893
The mind can act like an echoing chamber or an infinity mirror, detecting its last thought, reacting in the same way, escalating worries till we're a nervous wreck.

141
00:19:08,729 --> 00:19:13,016
Training ourselves to use the mind door wisely is our pathway to freedom.

142
00:19:14,357 --> 00:19:17,683
We can learn to stop echoing information unnecessarily.

143
00:19:18,565 --> 00:19:23,192
Stop trying to persuade ourselves that the past is still present.

144
00:19:23,212 --> 00:19:25,957
Persuade ourselves that thoughts represent reality.

145
00:19:28,621 --> 00:19:34,550
This shows us why so much emphasis is put on awareness at the physical sense doors in Vipassana.

146
00:19:37,196 --> 00:19:53,619
The more often we rest attention on physical sensations, the less chance we're giving the mind to go round in circles, thinking a thought, detecting the feelings and perceptions generated by the thought, reacting to them by generating another thought.

147
00:19:57,176 --> 00:20:08,295
We recognise the value of closing down the echo chamber effect of the mind when we stop rehearsing our woes, going over and over our plans, stop the daft daydreams.

148
00:20:09,376 --> 00:20:10,038
It's a relief.

149
00:20:11,601 --> 00:20:13,964
At times we detect a deeper silence.

150
00:20:15,788 --> 00:20:21,497
We might lose the sense of being an individual, a subjective entity to whom experience is happening.

151
00:20:22,844 --> 00:20:30,272
Sensations need no further embellishment, no interpretation beyond the experience of them arising and fading.

152
00:20:32,135 --> 00:20:43,569
Gradually we start to trust the Buddha's insight that Dukkha results from ignorance, from constructing a false version of reality because we are not seeing it clearly.

153
00:20:47,413 --> 00:20:53,083
The sense doors provide the opportunity for the sixth link to be made, sense contact.

154
00:20:54,365 --> 00:21:00,154
This happens when a sense door is open and has consciousness at one end and a sense object at the other.

155
00:21:01,576 --> 00:21:10,991
We've already mentioned sense contact, which can be confusing till you remember that all the first six links are experienced simultaneously.

156
00:21:12,153 --> 00:21:19,114
At the moment the vibrations fall on the ear, a mental image of sound appears on the screen of consciousness.

157
00:21:21,741 --> 00:21:26,195
The vibration is only known as its mental component within Nama.

158
00:21:27,323 --> 00:21:32,891
The bird may be singing in the tree, but the sound I hear is within my own mind.

159
00:21:33,971 --> 00:21:37,696
The thought, there's a bird singing in the tree, is a thought.

160
00:21:38,478 --> 00:21:42,323
It's a construction we're putting on reality to explain that sound.

161
00:21:45,166 --> 00:21:50,875
Sense contact forms the necessary basis for the next link, feeling, or vedana.

162
00:21:52,257 --> 00:21:56,082
We're hardwired to interpret whatever comes in through the sense doors.

163
00:21:57,799 --> 00:22:08,479
Our biology is designed to detect whether the environment is safe or threatening, whether there are opportunities out there we should avail of, like food, shelter, company.

164
00:22:10,122 --> 00:22:14,950
Once sense contact is made, the mind processes this to produce a feeling.

165
00:22:16,894 --> 00:22:22,743
Comparing this sense input to previous ones, it works out whether to signal pleasure or danger.

166
00:22:24,039 --> 00:22:28,345
If a match can be made with a good memory, a pleasant feeling is generated.

167
00:22:29,246 --> 00:22:32,549
If it's a bad memory, an unpleasant feeling results.

168
00:22:33,791 --> 00:22:39,097
If it matches up with memories that were not in any way special, then a neutral feeling is generated.

169
00:22:42,241 --> 00:22:47,067
Feelings, vedana in Pali, are also part of the mind.

170
00:22:47,909 --> 00:22:49,390
They're not out there in the world.

171
00:22:50,030 --> 00:22:53,355
They're internal, peculiar to each individual.

172
00:22:54,634 --> 00:22:56,096
We easily overlook this.

173
00:22:57,660 --> 00:23:00,904
We believe this person is terrific, beautiful, good fun.

174
00:23:02,106 --> 00:23:11,201
What we're doing is to project our internal feelings onto the person, embellishing them, concocting stories based on the good feeling we get when we meet them.

175
00:23:12,502 --> 00:23:16,067
But then we feel horribly let down if the person is in a bad humour.

176
00:23:17,790 --> 00:23:19,713
Our expectations aren't being met.

177
00:23:21,347 --> 00:23:26,336
Perplexed, we might add all manner of daft stories to the unpleasant feeling of disappointment.

178
00:23:27,156 --> 00:23:34,609
That they must be ill, that something terrible has happened, that they're rejecting us, that we've done something horrible to deserve a snub.

179
00:23:37,835 --> 00:23:45,346
If we can sensitise ourselves to our feelings, we can stop creating unnecessary stories around these.

180
00:23:46,660 --> 00:24:00,963
It helps undermine the reactive stories to let attention rest on feelings, discerning whether they are pleasant, unpleasant or neutral, whether they are associated with worldly concerns or with the spiritual life.

181
00:24:02,906 --> 00:24:05,632
This is a practice the Buddha specifically recommends.

182
00:24:08,336 --> 00:24:11,300
As we all know, however, this is not so easy.

183
00:24:13,086 --> 00:24:22,660
Our habit is to indulge feelings by forming the next link called tanha in Pali, translated as craving or desire.

184
00:24:25,723 --> 00:24:29,348
This, according to the Buddha, is the cause of all our suffering.

185
00:24:30,730 --> 00:24:33,473
We crave more of whatever gives us a pleasant feeling.

186
00:24:34,394 --> 00:24:36,597
We crave to get rid of unpleasant feelings.

187
00:24:37,559 --> 00:24:40,123
We crave to ignore neutral feelings.

188
00:24:42,652 --> 00:24:47,557
Unlike contact and feeling, craving isn't a basic constituents of mind.

189
00:24:49,340 --> 00:24:55,648
Contact, feeling and other elements of nama can be likened to atoms of experience.

190
00:24:57,270 --> 00:25:00,355
They can't be broken up, explored in more depth.

191
00:25:01,836 --> 00:25:10,988
We can be aware of these as entities in themselves, just as sensation, just as feeling tone, just as a mind state.

192
00:25:13,313 --> 00:25:17,759
Craving and all the links beyond craving aren't so simple.

193
00:25:20,703 --> 00:25:38,628
Remember, the cycle from ignorance to dukkha can happen thousands of times a second, so there is time for a thousand different sankharas to underlie a thousand feelings, sensations and perceptions in even one second of craving or clinging.

194
00:25:41,021 --> 00:25:49,993
It's like putting atoms together to form molecules, putting molecules together to form a cell, and so on, till we have a new being.

195
00:25:50,674 --> 00:25:55,721
When we're paying close attention, we can start to deconstruct the monster.

196
00:25:57,845 --> 00:26:07,096
We'll see that the experience of craving can be analysed down to several moments of sense contact, each with its own feeling tones.

197
00:26:09,440 --> 00:26:17,829
Physically craving is often felt as pulling or pushing, lack of force within the body, a strong flow of energy.

198
00:26:20,634 --> 00:26:24,417
Mentally, we might sense a willful focusing of mind.

199
00:26:25,339 --> 00:26:33,809
We get tunnel vision, all attention being drawn toward what we want or don't want, pushed away from what we want to ignore.

200
00:26:36,877 --> 00:26:42,557
Even though craving is the cause of suffering, we shouldn't repress it in Vipassana.

201
00:26:43,863 --> 00:26:46,332
We need to get to know the experience.

202
00:26:47,559 --> 00:26:59,017
If we find ourselves rushing towards the dining room for dinner, that's a great time to slow down, bring attention inward, feel the mental and physical energies that are compelling you to rush.

203
00:27:00,097 --> 00:27:05,226
Often, there will be a mixture of craving and the next link, clinging, at this stage.

204
00:27:05,967 --> 00:27:10,614
Clinging, Upadana in Pali, is sometimes called grasping.

205
00:27:12,777 --> 00:27:14,799
This generates a sense of self.

206
00:27:16,281 --> 00:27:33,858
It's as if many molecules of craving fuse together to create a central headquarters for this new activity, getting what I want, getting rid of what I don't want, ignoring what I deem irrelevant.

207
00:27:33,878 --> 00:27:42,406
Let's look at how we might recognise grasping, upadana, resulting from reacting with desire at the thought of buttered toast.

208
00:27:44,007 --> 00:27:49,961
Desire might have been felt as a rush of physical energy when the mind suddenly zoomed into that thought.

209
00:27:51,105 --> 00:27:56,880
A second later, those energies have coalesced into an empowered feeling of me.

210
00:27:58,002 --> 00:27:58,944
This is grasping.

211
00:28:00,393 --> 00:28:03,838
It might be felt as a solidifying within body and mind.

212
00:28:05,001 --> 00:28:08,488
A moment ago, experience may have been nebulous.

213
00:28:09,490 --> 00:28:14,419
Now it seems I'm a whole entire person with a very definite agenda.

214
00:28:19,276 --> 00:28:31,528
If we've previously trained ourselves to take an interest in the experience of craving, then sankaras of mindfulness could also be underlying consciousness, making us aware of greed.

215
00:28:33,269 --> 00:28:38,934
Sankaras of restraint could prompt us to think again, to hold back from indulgence.

216
00:28:40,916 --> 00:28:46,583
It often seems as though we have multiple selves, all pulling us in different directions.

217
00:28:47,811 --> 00:28:56,022
Again, it's important to allow the experience of clinging become fully known within Vipassana, rather than suppress this.

218
00:28:57,845 --> 00:29:00,548
Some of these selves we construct are wise.

219
00:29:02,951 --> 00:29:12,944
For example, the mindful, restrained aspects of our character can hold us in check while the greedy aspect is yelling for buttered toast.

220
00:29:14,205 --> 00:29:17,109
So we can welcome each experience of grasping.

221
00:29:18,202 --> 00:29:26,736
These give mindfulness a chance to learn how to grasp onto whatever safety hook might be available in times of trouble.

222
00:29:30,560 --> 00:29:33,164
Every greed will have its moment in the sun.

223
00:29:34,748 --> 00:29:40,936
For example, there may come a time when we're curled up in fear and dread of a scary world.

224
00:29:42,570 --> 00:29:49,763
At that moment, intuition might well choose a sankara of greed as the wisest basis for conscious experience.

225
00:29:50,765 --> 00:29:52,808
We grasp onto anything pleasant.

226
00:29:53,609 --> 00:29:57,457
Could be a thought like, there must be something better than this.

227
00:29:58,719 --> 00:30:05,912
It's wise to grasp this glimmer of hope with all our might until the spectre of fear has dissipated.

228
00:30:08,592 --> 00:30:15,559
With mindfulness, we learn how to grasp wisely till the need to grasp is over.

229
00:30:18,182 --> 00:30:25,030
If we're not being mindful, however, greedy Sankaras will easily get the upper hand and we're on to the next link.

230
00:30:26,412 --> 00:30:30,416
This is termed becoming, bhava in Pali.

231
00:30:32,499 --> 00:30:35,663
This is the moment when will becomes action.

232
00:30:37,313 --> 00:30:39,536
we start moving towards the toaster.

233
00:30:41,178 --> 00:30:45,263
What was a possibility, a potential, now becomes reality.

234
00:30:47,125 --> 00:30:48,669
It's sensed as a release.

235
00:30:49,829 --> 00:30:55,057
All those tensions stirred up by desire and grasping now have somewhere to go.

236
00:30:55,096 --> 00:30:59,202
At this moment, we create kamma.

237
00:31:01,916 --> 00:31:11,107
Acting on sankaras of greed strengthens this habit in our character, makes it more likely that greed will haunt us in the future.

238
00:31:15,093 --> 00:31:24,924
It could happen, of course, that we were mindful at the point of grasping, and instead of rushing towards the toaster, we've decided to act on the sankara of restraint.

239
00:31:26,047 --> 00:31:28,869
We make a firm decision not to make toast.

240
00:31:31,734 --> 00:31:40,586
It's often a good idea to make some physical activity here as well, so that the energies stirred up by the earlier stages have somewhere to go.

241
00:31:40,606 --> 00:31:47,996
For example, walking to a window, looking out, whatever will help reinforce the decision.

242
00:31:49,939 --> 00:31:51,981
Thoughts also involve will.

243
00:31:52,041 --> 00:32:00,712
And so when we make the decision, we also create karma, making it more likely that we'll be able to restrain ourselves in the future.

244
00:32:05,012 --> 00:32:10,686
But if we've been snared by greed, we run to the penultimate link, termed birth.

245
00:32:12,731 --> 00:32:15,819
We're making the toast, buttering it, eating it.

246
00:32:17,704 --> 00:32:21,334
We now have ten minutes or more where greed can have a field day.

247
00:32:22,798 --> 00:32:32,133
We might be daydreaming, worrying, thinking of a thousand different things throughout the process, hardly even noticing the taste of toast when it hits the tongue.

248
00:32:33,695 --> 00:32:45,634
Each thought, each mindless body movement sows more kama, getting us ever more hooked on greed, mindlessness, daydreams, worries and restlessness.

249
00:32:47,520 --> 00:32:54,770
If greed had prompted the birth of, say, a night in the pub getting drunk, the potential for harm would be even greater.

250
00:32:54,830 --> 00:33:06,406
This penultimate link, birth, sets our life on a certain trajectory which reinforces whatever habit prompts the activity in the first place.

251
00:33:10,973 --> 00:33:16,801
But even here, mindfulness might prevail, giving us a chance to limit the damage.

252
00:33:18,435 --> 00:33:24,063
we could decide to slow down, to relax and enjoy the treat of buttered toast.

253
00:33:25,765 --> 00:33:32,614
You might even decide to forego the last morsel, give it to the birds, as a symbolic step towards restraint.

254
00:33:34,355 --> 00:33:39,541
And of course we can take wholesome births, for example, going on retreat.

255
00:33:41,805 --> 00:33:46,671
Each step in dependent arising can be used wisely once we know what we're doing.

256
00:33:48,118 --> 00:33:52,346
and keep reminding yourself that the whole process is happening in any moment.

257
00:33:53,630 --> 00:34:04,490
So even if, at a gross level, we've taken birth as a toast eater, we can pause at any moment to feel the desires and clinging underlying this.

258
00:34:09,094 --> 00:34:23,190
As an aside, let's remember that dependent arising is occurring at many, many levels in life and we've all taken birth in various forms as a parent, a sister, an engineer.

259
00:34:24,913 --> 00:34:29,858
We took birth as a human being at our physical birth.

260
00:34:29,878 --> 00:34:33,802
All of these births are being acted out moment after moment.

261
00:34:37,630 --> 00:34:42,356
back to our mini birth as a devourer of buttered toast.

262
00:34:42,376 --> 00:34:48,324
Once the last crumb has disappeared, we have the final link in the chain, termed death.

263
00:34:51,427 --> 00:34:59,297
The Buddha describes this also as sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief and despair.

264
00:35:00,659 --> 00:35:02,001
The pleasure is over.

265
00:35:03,297 --> 00:35:10,206
All that's left are sticky teeth, a bloated tummy, dirty dishes and the need to buy more bread.

266
00:35:14,210 --> 00:35:24,405
The term death sounds melodramatic but as practice deepens we get more sensitive to the miseries we can experience when delusive pleasure comes to an end.

267
00:35:26,347 --> 00:35:32,054
On retreat some years ago I had been looking forward eagerly to the evening meal on my last day.

268
00:35:33,367 --> 00:35:36,632
With great relish, I sat down to a bowl of steaming soup.

269
00:35:38,215 --> 00:35:42,722
But as the bowl emptied, it was as if my world came to an end.

270
00:35:45,184 --> 00:35:47,188
Deep grief, believe it or not.

271
00:35:48,489 --> 00:35:50,313
Worldly pleasures don't last.

272
00:35:52,416 --> 00:35:55,380
Delusion gets us to ignore that obvious reality.

273
00:35:57,001 --> 00:36:02,429
We can pin all our hopes on the next meal, the next party, the next activity.

274
00:36:03,793 --> 00:36:12,324
Once they're over, discontent rears its head again, intensified because our latest hopes for happiness have been dashed.

275
00:36:15,307 --> 00:36:17,570
We might feel painfully disappointed.

276
00:36:23,777 --> 00:36:29,824
Usually, we skip quickly over this final link, busy ourselves with some new activity.

277
00:36:31,186 --> 00:36:33,108
But we'll never escape dukkha that way.

278
00:36:35,047 --> 00:36:39,592
Don't underestimate the value of mindfulness at this final stage of dukkha.

279
00:36:41,393 --> 00:36:46,137
If we're willing to feel our disappointment, this is a powerful teacher.

280
00:36:48,179 --> 00:36:52,744
In fact, many people start their spiritual journey because of some form of death.

281
00:36:54,626 --> 00:36:57,349
It might be a physical death, the loss of a loved one.

282
00:36:59,030 --> 00:37:04,817
It might be a relationship breakup, losing our job, failing an exam,

283
00:37:05,961 --> 00:37:07,643
seeing the first wrinkles appear.

284
00:37:09,246 --> 00:37:14,753
In some way or other, we are suddenly jolted into the more painful realities of life.

285
00:37:17,356 --> 00:37:24,527
Not knowing how to cope, we look for wisdom, for some alternative to a life based on temporary pleasures.

286
00:37:26,362 --> 00:37:36,518
So even if we've missed every single cue and ended up with toothache, bellyache and never want to see another slice of toast, it's possible to learn from this dukkha.

287
00:37:37,840 --> 00:37:44,371
Each and every mini-death we go through mindfully eats away at ignorance, our basic problem.

288
00:37:45,853 --> 00:37:51,443
I never again pinned so much hope on an evening meal following that grief-filled bowl of soup

289
00:37:55,253 --> 00:37:57,715
We undermine ignorance with wisdom.

290
00:37:59,157 --> 00:38:04,943
The better we know any of the links independent arising, the more wisdom we are gaining.

291
00:38:07,007 --> 00:38:13,775
So pick whichever one is most obvious at any time, or whichever naturally attracts your curiosity.

292
00:38:17,318 --> 00:38:20,922
The Buddha clarifies that we can halt the process at Vedana.

293
00:38:22,269 --> 00:38:27,298
we can become completely convinced that reactions of craving only lead to suffering.

294
00:38:28,740 --> 00:38:36,072
In tandem, we develop the taste for equanimity and tranquillity, for not allowing ignorance drive us to dukkha.

295
00:38:38,217 --> 00:38:44,126
With that, we can resist the allure of pleasant feeling and aversion towards the unpleasant.

296
00:38:45,456 --> 00:38:49,081
We don't have to suppress these reactions out of fear or judgment.

297
00:38:50,001 --> 00:38:55,306
Instead, we relax, trust wisdom to do the work.

298
00:38:55,327 --> 00:39:03,556
When we can dare to trust, intuitive intelligence can start to tease out ways to protect us from repeating the cycle.

299
00:39:06,739 --> 00:39:13,505
It can be fascinating to watch how the intuitive intelligence rescues us from our unskillful habits.

300
00:39:15,510 --> 00:39:21,597
What I sometimes find is that it uses some other habit to pull me back from the current of danger.

301
00:39:21,657 --> 00:39:29,244
For example, I might be watching anger and on the verge of strong condemnation.

302
00:39:30,786 --> 00:39:33,768
Many of the final links can be felt within experience.

303
00:39:34,829 --> 00:39:42,717
Tanha, craving, can be felt as a tense pushing within my body and my mind almost splitting in two.

304
00:39:45,262 --> 00:39:51,070
Grasping expresses itself as a solid sense of me, the righteous one.

305
00:39:52,351 --> 00:40:05,710
There's a feeling of power associated with this image of myself and it's almost as if my body is being shaped as a large fist which is clasping tightly around the mind state.

306
00:40:08,954 --> 00:40:12,400
All the earlier links are embedded within the experience too.

307
00:40:14,472 --> 00:40:25,452
The sensations of grasping include unpleasant feelings of tension, sweetly pleasant feelings of self-righteousness, the habitual formation of anger and so on.

308
00:40:27,978 --> 00:40:31,384
I teeter on the cusp of the next link becoming.

309
00:40:33,574 --> 00:40:36,518
This is sensed as if a dam is about to burst.

310
00:40:37,701 --> 00:40:44,510
I know that all my powerful, self-righteous energies could burst through the dam and be released into a torrent of angry thoughts.

311
00:40:45,972 --> 00:40:47,614
At times the dam bursts.

312
00:40:48,835 --> 00:40:53,842
This feels like a relief and pleasant feelings become more apparent.

313
00:40:55,384 --> 00:41:02,434
But because of mindfulness, these pleasant feelings might also get associated with perceptions of friendliness.

314
00:41:03,510 --> 00:41:04,992
This can change everything.

315
00:41:06,255 --> 00:41:11,704
Self-righteousness cools a bit, remembering the value of friendship.

316
00:41:11,724 --> 00:41:16,713
The Sankara of doubt might then become conscious, giving me pause for thought.

317
00:41:21,079 --> 00:41:26,228
This, I find, is a really interesting aspect of the whole process.

318
00:41:27,693 --> 00:41:36,342
A sankara of doubt is normally unskillful, but can be used skillfully by intuitive awareness in many situations.

319
00:41:37,802 --> 00:41:40,865
In this case, it's not arising out of ignorance.

320
00:41:42,407 --> 00:41:49,074
Mindfulness is present, and intuition senses doubt as my best route out of the mess I've created.

321
00:41:49,094 --> 00:41:57,041
This shows why we need to allow all our various habits be expressed in Vipassana.

322
00:41:57,577 --> 00:42:03,445
The more we get to know their expression, the more readily they can be used to rescue us from situations.

323
00:42:04,907 --> 00:42:08,893
Anger could be a wise route to stabilize us against fear, for example.

324
00:42:09,954 --> 00:42:12,137
Greed could help us move on from despair.

325
00:42:12,197 --> 00:42:17,224
There is hope, even within all our unskillful habits.

326
00:42:19,532 --> 00:42:25,018
At other times, the transition from craving to equanimity might be quite smooth.

327
00:42:25,498 --> 00:42:30,965
In fact, we might not even understand exactly why, but our attitude has changed.

328
00:42:32,186 --> 00:42:40,054
One moment we were fretting, doing our best to keep mindfulness afloat, but in constant danger of identifying with thoughts and feelings.

329
00:42:41,237 --> 00:42:42,637
The next moment...

330
00:42:42,617 --> 00:42:45,422
We're okay with the experience.

331
00:42:45,442 --> 00:42:52,913
The sensations and feelings are the same, but we're no longer identifying with these, no longer troubled by them.

332
00:42:53,893 --> 00:43:00,103
The teacher, Thanissaro Bhikkhu, puts this down to the complexity of dependent arising.

333
00:43:01,972 --> 00:43:15,356
As for an ecosystem or almost any aspect of modern society, the system has feedback loops which, in normal circumstances, positively reinforce the system, making it robust.

334
00:43:17,159 --> 00:43:20,965
But complex systems run into trouble when the environment changes.

335
00:43:22,568 --> 00:43:26,074
There are tipping points where the system becomes vulnerable.

336
00:43:27,657 --> 00:43:42,338
Once the tipping point has been reached, negative feedback starts to predominate and the system starts to fail and can even disintegrate, just as a bridge might suddenly collapse and as the financial system collapsed in 2008.

337
00:43:46,443 --> 00:43:50,289
Nowadays, we greatly fear ecosystem collapse.

338
00:43:50,927 --> 00:43:54,873
But within the sphere of dependent arising, collapse is welcome.

339
00:43:56,175 --> 00:44:07,751
We want to move towards that tipping point where our behaviour starts to change radically, where the whole complex tangle that ensnares us in suffering starts to unravel.

340
00:44:11,456 --> 00:44:15,282
The environment for dependent arising is wisdom.

341
00:44:17,572 --> 00:44:26,291
While this is at a low level, while we're ignorant, the system flourishes and binds us tightly into unskillful habits.

342
00:44:28,074 --> 00:44:33,827
But mindfulness chips away at ignorance, drives the system towards its tipping point.

343
00:44:35,731 --> 00:44:47,791
Once we start to see how dependent arising works, intuition can use our understanding to undermine the process and bring about the conditions which favour collapse.

344
00:44:51,257 --> 00:44:55,945
The system will collapse totally and forever at the moment of enlightenment.

345
00:44:57,668 --> 00:45:00,793
But we sense many disintegrations along the way.

346
00:45:02,612 --> 00:45:08,922
I mention these because we should welcome them but the sudden change might leave us perplexed.

347
00:45:11,206 --> 00:45:16,873
One example would be the abrupt attitude change from fretful to equanimous.

348
00:45:18,556 --> 00:45:20,940
Resistance can suddenly evaporate.

349
00:45:23,543 --> 00:45:27,168
At other times we might suddenly see through the fallacy of our thoughts.

350
00:45:28,177 --> 00:45:30,382
as if a veil had been lifted from our eyes.

351
00:45:31,664 --> 00:45:35,490
We wonder why we hadn't been able to see what was so totally obvious.

352
00:45:37,795 --> 00:45:45,568
At other times, it's as if we can feel threads of delusion snapping as we relax.

353
00:45:45,588 --> 00:45:50,557
One moment we're blowing up a bubble of thought, the next moment the bubble has burst.

354
00:45:53,204 --> 00:46:00,795
We can welcome all these abrupt changes as evidence that the system that binds us to dukkha is starting to crumble.

355
00:46:03,840 --> 00:46:11,652
Each moment of mindfulness undermines ignorance, drives the system that bit closer to its tipping point.

356
00:46:14,467 --> 00:46:31,480
I hope this talk encourages you to increase your understanding of dependent arising, getting to know whichever of the twelve links seems most apparent, trusting that this knowledge is bringing you closer to the end of suffering.

